 Here is the implementation of the classes according to the given specifications:

```java
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;

class Song {
    String name;
    String runTime;
    String singer;

    public Song(String nm, String rt, String sng) {
        name = nm;
        runTime = rt;
        singer = sng;
    }
}

class Playlist {
    List<Song> songs = new ArrayList<>();

    public String playSong(String currentTime, Song song) {
        // Assuming both currentTime and runTime are in the format "mm:ss"
        String[] currentTimeParts = currentTime.split(":");
        String[] runTimeParts = song.runTime.split(":");

        int currentMinutes = Integer.parseInt(currentTimeParts[0]);
        int currentSeconds = Integer.parseInt(currentTimeParts[1]);

        int runMinutes = Integer.parseInt(runTimeParts[0]);
        int runSeconds = Integer.parseInt(runTimeParts[1]);

        if (currentMinutes * 60 + currentSeconds < runMinutes * 60 + runSeconds) {
            return "Song is being continued";
        } else {
            return "Song replayed";
        }
    }

    public String addSong(Song song) {
        for (Song existingSong : songs) {
            if (existingSong.name.equals(song.name)) {
                return "Cannot be added";
            }
        }
        songs.add(song);
        return "Added";
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Playlist playlist = new Playlist();
        Song song1 = new Song("Venom", "4:58", "Eminem");
        System.out.println(playlist.addSong(song1)); // Output: Added
        System.out.println(playlist.addSong(song1)); // Output: Cannot be added
    }
}
```

This Java code defines the `Song` and `Playlist` classes as per the specifications and provides a sample `main` method for testing.
